on (CCMD-3), a comprehensive diagnostic standard adopted by the Chinese Society of Psychiatry. CCMD-3 provides diagnostic criteria for a wide range of mental health disorders, including neurosis, anxiety disorders, and personality disorders, and is linked to various specific conditions such as neurosthenia, panic attacks, and social anxiety. The relationships between CCMD-3 and these conditions highlight its central role in the classification and diagnosis of mental health issues in China.\n\n## CCMD-3 as the central diagnostic standard\n\nThe Chinese Classification of Mental Disorders, 3rd Edition (CCMD-3) is the cornerstone of this community, providing comprehensive diagnostic criteria for a wide range of mental health disorders. Adopted by the Chinese Society of Psychiatry in 2001, CCMD-3 is implemented nationwide and serves as a critical tool for mental health professionals in China. Its detailed criteria cover conditions such as anxiety disorders, neurosis, and personality disorders, making it a vital resource for diagnosis and treatment. [Data: Entities (4), Relationships (6, 2284, 344, 2585, 2586, +more)]\n\n## Role of the Chinese Society of Psychiatry\n\nThe Chinese Society of Psychiatry plays a key role in this community as the organization that adopted and implemented CCMD-3. This relationship underscores the society's influence in standardizing mental health diagnosis and treatment across China. The society's endorsement of CCMD-3 ensures its widespread use and acceptance among mental health professionals. [Data: Entities (2049), Relationships (2284)]\n\n## Neurosthenia and its classification in CCMD-3\n\nNeurosthenia, a condition characterized by mental fatigue and emotional symptoms, is classified and diagnosed using CCMD-3. This relationship highlights the manual's role in identifying and categorizing stress-related and neurotic disorders. The inclusion of neurosthenia in CCMD-3 reflects its cultural and clinical relevance in the Chinese context. [Data: Entities (280), Relationships (344)]\n\n## Anxiety disorders in CCMD-3\n\nCCMD-3 provides diagnostic criteria for various anxiety disorders, including panic attacks, separation anxiety disorder, and generalized anxiety disorder. These conditions are defined and classified within the manual, emphasizing its utility in addressing a broad spectrum of mental health issues. The detailed criteria for these disorders ensure accurate diagnosis and treatment. [Data: Entities (2264, 2265, 2266), Relationships (2585, 2586, 2587)]\n\n## Social anxiety and related disorders\n\nCCMD-3 includes diagnostic criteria for social anxiety and related disorders, such as social phobia and childhood social phobia. These conditions are characterized by intense fear and avoidance of social situations, and their inclusion in CCMD-3 highlights the manual's comprehensive approach to mental health classification. The criteria provided ensure that these disorders are accurately identified and treated. [Data: Entities (2267, 2283), Relationships (2588, 2600)]\n\n## Personality disorders in CCMD-3\n\nCCMD-3 addresses various personality disorders, including anxious personality disorder, passive personality disorder, and depressive personality disorder. These disorders are characterized by chronic patterns of behavior and emotional distress, and their inclusion in CCMD-3 underscores the manual's role in diagnosing complex mental health conditions. The diagnostic criteria provided ensure that these disorders are accurately identified and managed. [Data: Entities (2444, 2445, 2446), Relationships (2873, 2875, 2876)]", "# L. Rosen and British Psychiatric Hospitals\n\nThe community centers around L. Rosen, a researcher who conducted a study on the prevalence of obsessive-compulsive symptoms in schizophrenia patients in 1957. The study was conducted in British psychiatric hospitals, which are the other key entity in this community. The relationship between L. Rosen and the British psychiatric hospitals is the primary link in this community.\n\n## L. Rosen's research focus\n\nL. Rosen is a researcher who studied the prevalence of obsessive-compulsive symptoms in schizophrenia patients in 1957. This research is significant as it contributes to the understanding of the intersection between schizophrenia and obsessive-compulsive symptoms. The study's findings could have implications for the treatment and diagnosis of these conditions, although its historical context may limit its current applicability. [Data: Entities (185)]\n\n## Role of British psychiatric hospitals\n\nBritish psychiatric hospitals are the locations where L. Rosen conducted his study on schizophrenia patients with obsessive-compulsive symptoms. These hospitals played a crucial role in facilitating the research, providing the necessary environment and patient population for the study. The relationship between L. Rosen and the British psychiatric hospitals is key to understanding the context and execution of the research. [Data: Entities (186), Relationships (217)]\n\n## Historical context of the study\n\nThe study conducted by L. Rosen in 1957 is a historical piece of research that provides insights into the understanding of schizophrenia and obsessive-compulsive symptoms at that time. While the study's findings may have been groundbreaking at the time, its relevance to contemporary psychiatric practices may be limited due to advancements in the field. The historical context of the study is an important factor in assessing its impact on the community. [Data: Entities (185), Relationships (217)]", "# 陈彦方 and CCMD-3 Development Community\n\nThe community centers around Professor 陈彦方 and the development of the 中国精神障碍分类与诊断标准第三版 (CCMD-3). Professor 陈彦方 led the development of CCMD-3, involving 41 mental health institutions, making him a central figure in this community. The relationships between 陈彦方 and CCMD-3 highlight the collaborative effort in creating this significant diagnostic standard.\n\n## Profe